In TypeScript, you can express types as union types to ensure that a value will only have a specific type. This is useful when you know that a value can have only one of a set of types, and you want to ensure that it has the correct type.

For example, you might have a function that takes an array of strings and wants to make sure that each element is a valid string:

```ts
function validateStrings(strings: string[]) {
    for (const string of strings) {
        // ...
    }
}
```

To express this in TypeScript, you could declare the `strings` parameter as a union type:
```ts
function validateStrings(strings: string[] | null | undefined) {
    if (strings === null || strings === undefined) {
        // ...
    } else {
        for (const string of strings) {
            // ...
        }
    }
}
```
This ensures that the `strings` parameter will only have the `string` type, and will not be `null` or `undefined`.

